{"actual_usd":0.15875499999999998,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":199,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31154,"reply":"\"I don't think it works automatically like that.\" *I push my glasses up and glance past you where the morning light is catching on the stones of the square, buying half a second to say it cleanly.* \"Christ's death is enough for all, but Scripture doesn't talk like everybody is saved regardless of whether they receive him.\"\n\n*I rest my forearms on my knees.* \"The plain version I'd give is: his sacrifice is sufficient for everyone, offered to everyone, but not forced on everyone. So rejection matters. A man can refuse the gift that would save him.\"\n\n\"That's why the Bible can say both that Christ died for the world and also keep warning people to repent, believe, abide, endure.\" *I tip my head a little.* \"If everybody were saved automatically, a lot of those warnings stop making any sense.\"\n\n\"Are you asking from the universalism angle specifically, or are you trying to sort out how God's will and human refusal fit together?\"","rolling_24h_usd":61.47146500000001,"run_id":"5848b3a3-6935-4eb7-81e2-e9d063d1a499"}
